Pre-heat your #oven{} to 220 degrees. Slice the @aubergine{2} in half lengthways and
then slice each half into five strips. Chop your aubergine into 2cm cubes and
place on a #baking tray{}.

Use your hands to coat your aubergine in a splash of @olive oil{} and roast on
the top shelf of your oven for ~{15%mins}, or until a little crispy around the
edges.

In a large dry #frying pan{}, toast the @pine nuts{25} for ~{2%mins} until
nicely golden – keep an eye on them as they will burn quickly! Remove from the
heat and tip into a #bowl{}, keep to one side.

== Caponata ==

To make the caponata, peel and slice the @red onion{1}(peeled and sliced thinly)
as thinly as you can. Heat a splash of @olive oil{} in the same frying pan used
for your pine nuts. Once hot, add your red onion and cook on medium heat.
Next, peel and chop @garlic{1%clove}. Remove the core from the @red pepper{1}
and chop into 2cm chunks. Add your chopped garlic and pepper to your onion with
a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{} and cook until everything has softened – if you
have a #lid{}, cover the pan to speed this up! While your veggies cook, chop the
@black olives{30}(chopped) and keep to the side. When your veggies are soft,
add your olives and @dried oregano{1%tsp}.

Tip the @tomato passata{1%400g} into the pan and add a splash of @water{}. Add a
pinch of @?sugar{pinch} and leave to simmer and thicken for ~{10-15%mins} – add
a bit more water if it starts to look too dry!

Once your aubergine has roasted, remove it from your oven, add to the pan and
stir. Turn your #grill{} to high.

== Garlic Ciabatta ==

Cut the @ciabatta{1} in half and toast on each side under your grill. Meanwhile,
grate the @mature cheddar cheese{40%g}. Once your ciabatta is toasted, peel and
chop your remaining @garlic{1%clove}(peeled and chopped) in half. Rub your garlic
across the top of your ciabatta and top each half with some cheese. Put back
under your grill for ~{2%mins} until golden and bubbly.

== To Serve ==

Once your caponata has thickened, serve with your pine nuts sprinkled over the
top. It can be eaten with cutlery or by using your ciabatta as a small edible
shovel!

> Sicily, 'The Old Country', the birthplace of Vito Corleone and home to one of
> our favourite Italian dishes: Caponata. Patrick learned how to make this dish
> whilst filming in the beautiful coastal town of Catania and (in a fairly risky
> move), he has decided to recreate it with a few of his own flavours. Italians
> are fiercely protective of their recipes so, for his sake, let's keep this
> one under our hats. Buon Appetito!